<DOC><DOCNO> AP880327-0070 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-88 1711EST</FILEID><FIRST>r p AM-PoliticalBriefs     03-27 0460</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Political Briefs,440</SECOND><HEAD>Daily News Poll Indicates Bush, Dukakis New York Front-Runners</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   With the New York primary less than a monthaway, a poll published Sunday suggested Massachusetts Gov. MichaelDukakis and Vice President George Bush were the clear favoritesamong Democratic and Republican voters across the state.   The Daily News poll had Dukakis favored by 45 percent of theDemocrats surveyed. His closest rival was Jesse Jackson, preferredby 29 percent of the Democrats.   None of the three other active Democratic candidates was favoredby more than 6 percent of the voters who participated in thesurvey. Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt was favored by 6 percent,Illinois Sen. Paul Simon by 5 percent and Tennessee Sen. AlbertGore by 5 percent.   On the Republican side, voters surveyed favored Bush by 68percent, Kansas Sen. Bob Dole by 23 percent and former televisionevangelist Pat Roberson by 4 percent.   Although Dukakis was strongly favored by the Democrats polled,it is still clear that New York Democrats would like to see Gov.Mario Cuomo in the race for the nomination.   When those surveyed were asked about a presidential race thatincluded Cuomo, the support for Dukakis sharply diminished. Cuomowas favored by 59 percent and Dukakis dropped to third place in thestanding with 13 percent. Jackson was still in second place amongNew York Democrats, but his support dropped to 16 percent.   The poll was conducted for the Daily News by Chilton ResearchServices of Radnor, Pa. It surveyed 528 Democrats and 496Republicans who said they intended to vote in the primary. The pollwas conducted between Monday, March 21 and Thursday, March 24 andhas a margin for error of plus or minus 4.5 percentage points.   The New York primary is April 19.</TEXT><HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Gain Dramatically In Utah</HEAD><DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Vice President George Bush andMassachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis have made dramatic gains inrecent weeks in Utah, a poll suggests.   The change came after both Bush and Dukakis had wins to point toon Super Tuesday, March 8, which featured a big round of primariesand caucuses.   Dukakis leads Rep. Richard Gephardt 32 percent to 8 percent andBush leads Bob Dole 47 percent to 29 percent, according to a surveyby pollster Dan Jones andamp; Associates, which conducting the poll takenMarch 18 for the Deseret News and KSL-TV.   An earlier poll by the same organization, on February 24-25,found that Dole was favored over Bush, 39 percent to 32 percent. Onthe Democratic side, Gephardt was behind Dukakis, but by a muchsmaller margin, 30 percent to 20 percent.   The polls of 605 Utahs have an error margin of plus or minus 4percentage points.</TEXT></DOC>